            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVIII.R9</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Italian character</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-bc4c0d9a-7fff-4d5a-0b07-1900816c04d5\"><br />The reference to the &ldquo;Italian character&rdquo; likely refers in part to Cavalletto&rsquo;s language (lengthening adverbs and a &ldquo;significant Italian rest&rdquo; on certain words [LD 722]) and his mode of accounting for his search for Rigaud, and in part to the chapter&rsquo;s emphasis on Cavalletto&rsquo;s &ldquo;very remarkable combination of character,&rdquo; a &ldquo;blending&hellip; of his old submission with a sense of something humorous; the striving of that with a certain smouldering ferocity&rdquo; (LD 727). We might be reminded of the note for No. I in which Cavalletto was first introduced: &ldquo;Picture of an Italian&rdquo; (LD.I.R4).</span></p>"
        }
